      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Vendor</span><span class="meta-value">Majestic</span></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Citation Flow</strong> is a Majestic SEO metric scored from <strong>0 to 100</strong> that predicts how influential a URL or domain is based on the number of sites linking to it. It measures link popularity — quantity, not quality — and is most useful when paired with <strong>Trust Flow</strong> to reveal whether a link profile is genuinely authoritative or artificially inflated.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Vendor</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Majestic SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Scale</div>
            <div class="tms-value">0 – 100</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Measures</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Link quantity</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Pair with</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Trust Flow</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Citation Flow answers one question: how many pages link to this URL? It says nothing about whether those pages are trusted. That's why link builders never look at Citation Flow alone — the number tells you volume, and the Trust Flow ratio tells you whether the volume is real or noise.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is Citation Flow?</h2>
        <p>Citation Flow is a Majestic-proprietary metric introduced as a companion to <a href="/glossary/trust-flow/">Trust Flow</a>. Together they form Majestic's Flow Metrics — the vendor's answer to Moz's Domain Authority and Ahrefs' Domain Rating.</p>
        <p>Where competing metrics blend quantity and quality into one score, Majestic deliberately keeps them separate:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Citation Flow</strong> — how many links point at the URL or domain</li>
          <li><strong>Trust Flow</strong> — how trustworthy those linking sources are, based on proximity to seed-set trusted sites</li>
          <li><strong>Ratio</strong> — Trust Flow / Citation Flow reveals link profile health</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why the split matters</div>
          <p>A URL can hit <strong>Citation Flow 60</strong> from 10,000 spammy blog comments. The same URL might have <strong>Trust Flow 8</strong> — proving the 60 was cheap. Composite metrics like DA or DR hide this pattern; Majestic surfaces it by design.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why Citation Flow matters for SEO</h2>
        <p>Four reasons SEO teams still track Citation Flow in 2026:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Volume confirmation.</strong> A quick sense of whether a URL has any backlink footprint at all, correlating loosely with search visibility.</li>
          <li><strong>Spam detection.</strong> Big gaps between Citation Flow and Trust Flow are the fastest way to spot low-quality profile inflation.</li>
          <li><strong>Competitive analysis.</strong> Benchmarking against direct competitors reveals who is attracting more links, independent of quality.</li>
          <li><strong>Link prospect vetting.</strong> Before pursuing an outreach target, checking CF confirms the site has enough link equity to be worth the effort.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Citation Flow is calculated</h2>
        <p>Majestic computes Citation Flow by analyzing the number and connectivity of inbound links using a recursive model similar in spirit to Google's original PageRank formulation — pages with more inbound links score higher, and links from high-CF pages pass more citation authority than links from low-CF pages.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Simplified Citation Flow logic</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Input:</span> Majestic's index of the web<br>
          <span class="uf-label">For each URL:</span> count inbound links + weight by source CF<br>
          <span class="uf-label">Normalize:</span> to a 0–100 log scale<br>
          <span class="uf-label">Output:</span> URL-level and domain-level Citation Flow scores
        </div>

        <h3>The Trust Ratio</h3>
        <p>The most-used derived metric. Divide Trust Flow by Citation Flow:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Ratio above 0.7</strong> — high quality profile; trust is keeping pace with volume</li>
          <li><strong>Ratio 0.4 to 0.7</strong> — average; mix of trusted and untrusted links</li>
          <li><strong>Ratio below 0.4</strong> — likely low-quality inflation; approach with caution</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Practical application</h3>
        <p>Never make decisions on CF alone. Always view CF and TF side by side. A prospect at CF 40 / TF 32 is a strong link target. A prospect at CF 55 / TF 12 is a PBN warning.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Citation Flow benchmarks by site type</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Site type</th><th>Typical CF</th><th>Healthy TF/CF ratio</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Small local business</strong></td>
                <td>15 – 35</td>
                <td class="cell-yes">0.5+</td>
                <td>Ratio matters more than raw score</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Regional service brand</strong></td><td>30 – 45</td><td class="cell-yes">0.5+</td><td>Watch for local link farms inflating CF</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>National brand / SaaS</strong></td><td>40 – 60</td><td class="cell-yes">0.5+</td><td>Backlink budgets show up here</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Major publication</strong></td><td>70+</td><td class="cell-yes">0.6+</td><td>News tier</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Suspicious profile</strong></td><td>50+</td><td class="cell-no">Below 0.3</td><td>Likely bought links or PBN inflation</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real Citation Flow examples</h2>

        <h3>1. Two law firms, same CF, different quality</h3>
        <p>Two competing law firms sit at Citation Flow 42. Firm A has Trust Flow 34 (ratio 0.81) — clean profile built from bar association listings and legal directories. Firm B has Trust Flow 9 (ratio 0.21) — same CF built from paid guest posts on low-authority blogs. Firm A ranks in the local pack; Firm B doesn't.</p>

        <h3>2. Publisher tracking link health monthly</h3>
        <p>A content publisher tracks both CF and TF monthly. CF trends up steadily (link acquisition working) while TF stays flat — a warning that the new links are low quality. The team pivots outreach to editorial placements; three months later TF starts climbing to match.</p>

        <h3>3. PBN detection during outreach</h3>
        <p>An SEO reviewing 30 outreach prospects filters out 8 with CF above 40 but TF below 15. Two of the eight turn out to be full PBNs; the other six are low-quality directory sites. The filter saved a week of wasted email sends.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Citation Flow vs Trust Flow — the metric pair</h2>
        <p>Two halves of the same picture. Neither is useful without the other.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Citation Flow measures</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Link quantity and popularity</li>
              <li>Number of inbound links</li>
              <li>Weighted by source citation authority</li>
              <li>Can be inflated by any linking pattern</li>
              <li>Correlates loosely with search visibility</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Trust Flow measures</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Link quality and trustworthiness</li>
              <li>Proximity to Majestic's seed trust set</li>
              <li>Weighted by source trust authority</li>
              <li>Resistant to bought / spam link inflation</li>
              <li>Correlates more tightly with ranking outcomes</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for using Citation Flow</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Never look at CF alone.</strong> Always pair with Trust Flow. The pair is the point of the metric.</li>
          <li><strong>Use the ratio, not the raw score.</strong> TF / CF above 0.5 is the working heuristic for healthy profiles.</li>
          <li><strong>Benchmark against competitors.</strong> Absolute CF numbers mean little; competitor deltas mean everything.</li>
          <li><strong>Vet outreach prospects.</strong> Filter your outreach list for TF / CF ratio above 0.5 before sending emails.</li>
          <li><strong>Track monthly, not daily.</strong> Majestic's index updates on a monthly-ish cadence. Daily tracking adds noise, not signal.</li>
          <li><strong>Cross-check with a second vendor.</strong> Compare Majestic CF against Ahrefs UR or Moz DA to catch anomalies before making decisions.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — chasing high CF</div>
          <p>Buying links from "high CF domains" is a classic tactic that fails. If the seller can raise their CF cheaply, the CF isn't worth much — that's exactly why the seller can afford to sell to you. Trust Flow is the metric worth paying for.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common Citation Flow mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Using CF as a single-metric decision</strong> — always pair with TF</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring the ratio</strong> — raw scores mislead</li>
          <li><strong>Comparing to absolute benchmarks</strong> — CF is niche-relative</li>
          <li><strong>Trusting "high CF" link seller pitches</strong> — cheap-to-inflate metric</li>
          <li><strong>Confusing CF with Domain Authority</strong> — different formulas, different indexes</li>
          <li><strong>Refreshing daily</strong> — the index doesn't update that fast</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Is Citation Flow the same as Domain Authority?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>No. Citation Flow is Majestic's link quantity metric; Domain Authority is Moz's composite score weighing both quantity and quality. They approximate similar things but use different data sets and formulas.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Can Citation Flow be manipulated?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes. Spammy or bought links inflate Citation Flow without improving search performance. Majestic's Trust Flow is designed to catch this — a high Citation Flow with a low Trust Flow signals manipulation.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What's a good Citation Flow score?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>It's niche-relative. Small local businesses typically sit at 15 to 35, national brands at 40 to 60, and major publications at 70 or above. Always benchmark against direct competitors, not absolute numbers.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How do I use Citation Flow for link building?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Check both Citation Flow and Trust Flow before pursuing a link. A prospect with Citation Flow above 20 and a Trust Flow / Citation Flow ratio above 0.5 is generally worth pursuing. Skip prospects with high CF and low TF — they're probably PBNs.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Does Google use Citation Flow?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>No. Citation Flow is a third-party Majestic metric, not a Google ranking signal. It's a proxy that correlates with the underlying signals Google actually uses.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

